user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following metal_dma_map code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 8.13.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13 is A pointer should point to a const-qualified type whenever possible.

</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of metal_dma_map.
```c
int metal_dma_map(struct metal_device *dev,
		  uint32_t dir,
		  struct metal_sg *sg_in,
		  int nents_in,
		  struct metal_sg *sg_out)
{
	int nents_out;

	if (!dev || !sg_in || !sg_out)
		return -EINVAL;
	if (!dev->bus->ops.dev_dma_map)
		return -ENODEV;

	/* memory barrier */
	if (dir == METAL_DMA_DEV_R)
		/* If it is device read, apply memory write fence. */
		atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_release);
	else
		/* If it is device write or r/w, apply memory r/w fence. */
		atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_acq_rel);
	nents_out = dev->bus->ops.dev_dma_map(dev->bus,
			dev, dir, sg_in, nents_in, sg_out);
	return nents_out;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The metal_device member 'struct metal_bus *bus' is used only for read access (e.g. in metal_dma_map the code reads dev->bus->ops.dev_dma_map and calls it); the pointer could be declared as 'const struct metal_bus *bus' to indicate the device does not modify the bus object. Because the pointer is not const-qualified while it can be, this violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 8.13.
</scenario>
